13. laeta, ‘rich,' ‘luxuriant,’ a constant epithet of such words as fruges, pabula, segetes. Clitumnus is a river in Umbria, the meadows on whose banks supplied a breed of white oxen which are repeatedly mentioned as the choicest victims.

The animal is first called sanguis, and then cervix, much as an elephant is called ebur l. 112: this is hardly tolerable in English, so transl, ‘whose blood (ie. race) proclaims the rich pastures of Clitumnus, and whose neck needs a tall sacrificer to strike the blow.’
